\id JUD - The English New Testament According to Family 35
\h Jude
\toc3 Jude
\toc2 Jude
\toc1 The Epistle of Jude
\mt2 The Epistle of
\mt1 JUDE
\c 1
\s1 Salutation
\m 
\v 1 \w Jude|strong="G2455"\w*, \w slave|strong="G1401"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* brother \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w James|strong="G2385"\w*,\f + \fr 1:1 \ft Both James and Jude were half-brothers of Jesus (same mother) but were themselves full brothers. Jude avoids any special claim to that half-brotherhood and declares himself a slave.\f* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w called|strong="G2822"\w*, \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w been|strong="G2532"\w* sanctified\f + \fr 1:1 \ft Rather than “sanctified”, about 9% of the Greek manuscripts read ‘beloved’ (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* \w by|strong="G1722"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w preserved|strong="G5083"\w*\f + \fr 1:1 \ft By using words like “called”, “sanctified” and “preserved”, Jude is emphasizing God's part in our salvation.\f* \w through|strong="G1722"\w*\f + \fr 1:1 \ft “Jesus Christ” is in the dative case, without an explicit preposition, so we are faced with an ambiguous construction—it could be ‘by’, making Jesus Christ the agent; or if the Father is the agent it could be ‘for’ or ‘in’ as well as “through”.\f* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*:
\v 2 \w May|strong="G2532"\w* \w mercy|strong="G1656"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w peace|strong="G1515"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* love \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w multiplied|strong="G4129"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*.\f + \fr 1:2 \ft The verb is in the passive voice, so these things will be supplied by an outside power.\f*
\s1 Why he is writing
\p 
\v 3 Dear ones, \w while|strong="G3956"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* really intent \w on|strong="G4012"\w* \w writing|strong="G1125"\w* \w to|strong="G4160"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w salvation|strong="G4991"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* share, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w had|strong="G2192"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* compulsion\f + \fr 1:3 \ft I believe he is claiming inspiration here.\f* \w to|strong="G4160"\w* \w write|strong="G1125"\w* \w exhorting|strong="G3870"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w to|strong="G4160"\w* \w contend|strong="G1864"\w* \w earnestly|strong="G1864"\w* \w for|strong="G4012"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w Faith|strong="G4102"\w*\f + \fr 1:3 \ft Wherein might “the Faith” consist? Jude evidently contrasts it with what the “certain men” of verse 4 believe, teach and do, as explained in the following verses. I take it that for Jude “the Faith” refers to the sum of Biblical values, the Biblical worldview or philosophy of life. It has been “committed” to us to put into practice, but also to defend. Who in North America or Europe is ‘contending for the Faith’, even a little bit? Both those continents are now anti-Christian.\f* once \w for|strong="G4012"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w committed|strong="G4160"\w* \w to|strong="G4160"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* saints.
\v 4 \w Because|strong="G1063"\w* \w certain|strong="G5100"\w* \w men|strong="G3778"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w marked|strong="G4270"\w* \w out|strong="G2532"\w* \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w condemnation|strong="G2917"\w* \w long|strong="G3819"\w* \w ago|strong="G3819"\w*,\f + \fr 1:4 \ft This is one of a very few texts that could be used to defend the doctrine of preterition, or double predestination (that the lost are predestined to be lost).\f* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* sneaked \w in|strong="G1519"\w*; \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* godless, perverting \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w grace|strong="G5485"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* licentiousness \w and|strong="G2532"\w* denying \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w only|strong="G3441"\w* Sovereign \w God|strong="G2316"\w*,\f + \fr 1:4 \ft About 13% of the Greek manuscripts omit “God” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*.
\s1 Examples from ancient history
\p 
\v 5 \w So|strong="G1161"\w* \w I|strong="G1161"\w* \w want|strong="G1014"\w* \w to|strong="G1014"\w* \w remind|strong="G5279"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w though|strong="G1161"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* already \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w this|strong="G3588"\w*, \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w delivered|strong="G5210"\w* \w a|strong="G3708"\w* \w people|strong="G2992"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w land|strong="G1093"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* Egypt \w yet|strong="G1161"\w* \w later|strong="G1208"\w* destroyed \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w did|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w*.\f + \fr 1:5 \ft It is not wise to presume upon God's goodness—He demands commitment. Less than half of those who left Egypt entered the promised land.\f*
\v 6 \w And|strong="G5037"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* angels \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w did|strong="G3361"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w keep|strong="G5083"\w* \w their|strong="G1438"\w* \w proper|strong="G2398"\w* domain \w but|strong="G3361"\w* deserted\f + \fr 1:6 \ft If they had to ‘desert’ their domain and dwelling in order to acquire the ability to procreate with women, the implication may be that their decision was irrevocable—they could not go back.\f* \w their|strong="G1438"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* \w dwelling|strong="G3613"\w* \w He|strong="G3588"\w* \w has|strong="G2920"\w* \w kept|strong="G5083"\w* bound \w in|strong="G1519"\w* everlasting \w chains|strong="G1199"\w* \w under|strong="G5259"\w* \w darkness|strong="G2217"\w* \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w judgment|strong="G2920"\w* \w of|strong="G5259"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w great|strong="G3173"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*.\f + \fr 1:6 \ft The place is called Tartarus in 2 Peter 2:4. Comparing this passage with 1 Peter 3:19-20 and 2 Peter 2:4-5 and Genesis 6:2,4, it seems clear that certain angelic beings cohabited with women, producing a mongrel race, the \it nephilim\it*. (The phrase ‘sons of God’ in Gen. 6:2,4 is a translation of the Hebrew phrase \it bene haelohim\it*—the only other places this phrase occurs are in Job 1:6, 2:1 and 38:7, where the reference is clearly to angelic beings.) This was such a heinous crime that God incarcerated them millennia before the victory of Christ (that would justify the procedure; that is what He went to announce, as mentioned in 1 Peter 3:19). It was also a master stroke by Satan—since the male sperm transmits the human nature (Hebrews 7:9-10, Romans 5:12) and determines the blood of any child, if Satan had succeeded in contaminating the whole race, the Messiah could not be born and Genesis 3:15 could not be fulfilled.\f*
\v 7 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w Sodom|strong="G4670"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w Gomorrah|strong="G1116"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* surrounding \w towns|strong="G4172"\w*—\w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w gave|strong="G2532"\w* \w themselves|strong="G1438"\w* \w up|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w fornication|strong="G1608"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G2532"\w* \w after|strong="G3694"\w* \w a|strong="G5613"\w* \w different|strong="G2087"\w* kind \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w*\f + \fr 1:7 \ft Recall that they wanted to rape the angels. Whatever kind of ‘flesh’ an angel has when he materializes, it is not human.\f* \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w a|strong="G5613"\w* \w manner|strong="G5158"\w* \w similar|strong="G3664"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* angels—\w stand|strong="G3778"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w an|strong="G2532"\w* \w example|strong="G1164"\w*, \w undergoing|strong="G5254"\w* \w a|strong="G5613"\w* \w punishment|strong="G1349"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* eternal \w fire|strong="G4442"\w*.\f + \fr 1:7 \ft Just as ‘eternal life’ refers primarily to a quality of life, I take it that “eternal fire” here refers to a quality of fire—at the destruction of Sodom God used ‘brimstone and fire’ (Genesis 19:24), and the eternal Lake contains ‘fire and brimstone’ (Revelation 20:10).\f*
\s1 Evil men are in the church
\p 
\v 8 \w Likewise|strong="G3668"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w dreamers|strong="G1797"\w* \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* turn \w both|strong="G2532"\w* \w defile|strong="G3392"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w*\f + \fr 1:8 \ft The Text has just those two words, “defile flesh”, which makes it difficult to be dogmatic about the meaning; perhaps the most common interpretation takes it as referring to their own bodies, presumably by unnatural sex.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* reject \w authority|strong="G2963"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* slander celestial beings.\f + \fr 1:8 \ft The Text has ‘glories’, but because of verse 9 it seems likely that the reference is to angelic beings.\f*
\v 9 \w Yet|strong="G1161"\w* \w even|strong="G1161"\w* \w Michael|strong="G3413"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* archangel,\f + \fr 1:9 \ft Michael is now “\nd the\nd* archangel”, the boss angel, the commander of the heavenly army (Revelation 12:7).\f* \w when|strong="G3753"\w* taking \w issue|strong="G1252"\w* \w with|strong="G4012"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w devil|strong="G1228"\w*—\w he|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w arguing|strong="G1256"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w*' corpse\f + \fr 1:9 \ft Where did Jude get this information? I always assumed that Moses went up Nebo alone (and since he did not return there would be no human witness), but the Text does not actually say so. Could it be possible that Joshua went along? Whether Joshua wrote it or God revealed it to someone, I take it that a written record was made and that Jude had access to a copy in his day. Being true information the Holy Spirit moved him to include it in his letter, which became the only inspired account of those details.\f*—\w did|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w dare|strong="G5111"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w pronounce|strong="G2018"\w* \w a|strong="G1161"\w* reviling \w judgment|strong="G2920"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w May|strong="G3004"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w rebuke|strong="G2008"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*!”\f + \fr 1:9 \ft For years I wondered why God included verse 9 in an inspired letter; what difference does it make what happened to Moses' corpse? I now understand that the corpse is a mere prop, the crucial thing being the relationship between the two boss angels—one the leader of the good ones and the other the leader of the bad ones. We understand from Isaiah 14:12-15 and Ezekiel 28:12-17 that Lucifer was created the number one angel, but when he rebelled against the Creator I assumed that he was demoted. In such an event Michael (I assume he was the original number two) the archangel (there is only one) would be superior to Satan and be able to order him away. But the Text says he did not ‘dare’ to be disrespectful, but had to content himself with appealing to God for help. Against my inclination, I feel obliged to conclude that Lucifer (now Satan) was not demoted—he continues higher in rank than Michael. The same would hold for the other angelic beings that followed Lucifer (Daniel 10:13, 20-21; Ephesians 6:12)—they maintain their original rank. \nd However\nd*, what Michael did not dare do, we can. According to Ephesians 1:20-21 and 2:6, we who are in Christ are seated with Him far above all principality, power, etc. (the angelic hierarchy, good and bad). In Christ we are above Satan and may rebuke him directly (but do not forget James 4:7).\f*
\v 10 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w speak|strong="G1161"\w* abusively \w against|strong="G1722"\w* \w whatever|strong="G3745"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w do|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w understand|strong="G1492"\w*, \w while|strong="G1722"\w* \w whatever|strong="G3745"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w by|strong="G1722"\w* \w instinct|strong="G5447"\w*, \w like|strong="G5613"\w* unreasoning \w animals|strong="G2226"\w*—\w by|strong="G1722"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* ruined.\f + \fr 1:10 \ft Those people were evidently rather crass materialists, controlled by their body's appetites. We have to eat to live, but those who live to eat ruin themselves.\f*
\v 11 \w Woe|strong="G3759"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* taken \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w way|strong="G3598"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w Cain|strong="G2535"\w*,\f + \fr 1:11 \ft Since people and animals were vegetarians before the Flood, Abel did not raise sheep for food—so why did he do it? It seems to me obvious that God must have given Adam instruction, after the Fall, about the necessity of animal sacrifice to cover their sins. To Cain, the rationalist, that didn't make sense, so he chose to worship God in his own way. When rejected he rebelled against God and even killed his brother; those who choose evil usually hate the good, because the good shows them up.\f* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w rushed|strong="G1632"\w* \w into|strong="G4198"\w* Balaam's \w error|strong="G4106"\w* \w for|strong="G3754"\w* profit,\f + \fr 1:11 \ft Balaam prostituted his divine gift for material gain. Not only were there such people in Jude's day, there is no lack of such in ours.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* destroyed themselves \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w Korah|strong="G2879"\w*'s rebellion!\f + \fr 1:11 \ft Korah rebelled against God's established order—he wanted to be priest but was not a descendant of Aaron (though he was a Levite). He was not satisfied with the place God had allotted him.\f*
\p 
\v 12 \w These|strong="G3778"\w* \w men|strong="G3778"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w hidden|strong="G4694"\w* \w reefs|strong="G4694"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w your|strong="G1722"\w* love feasts, joining \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w feast|strong="G4910"\w* \w without|strong="G1438"\w* fear, \w caring|strong="G4165"\w* \w only|strong="G1438"\w* \w for|strong="G1722"\w* \w themselves|strong="G1438"\w*; \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w clouds|strong="G3507"\w* \w without|strong="G1438"\w* rain, \w carried|strong="G3911"\w* \w along|strong="G1722"\w* \w by|strong="G1722"\w* winds; \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* late \w autumn|strong="G5352"\w* \w trees|strong="G1186"\w* \w without|strong="G1438"\w* fruit, \w twice|strong="G1364"\w* dead (having \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w uprooted|strong="G1610"\w*);
\v 13 \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* wild \w waves|strong="G2949"\w* \w of|strong="G2281"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w sea|strong="G2281"\w*, foaming \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w their|strong="G1438"\w* \w own|strong="G1438"\w* shameful acts; \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w wandering|strong="G4107"\w* stars, \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w black|strong="G2217"\w* \w of|strong="G2281"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w darkness|strong="G4655"\w* \w has|strong="G3739"\w* been \w reserved|strong="G5083"\w* \w forever|strong="G1519"\w*.\f + \fr 1:13 \ft “The darkness” is characteristic of Satan's kingdom. Those who promote humanistic, relativistic, materialistic ideas and values in the church are really ‘party-crashers’, agents of Satan's kingdom. Jude's description of such people could scarcely be more violent or abusive—they have a special spot reserved in a really black corner of the darkness, throughout eternity. Servants of Satan who pretend to be Christians are too despicable for words.\f*
\p 
\v 14 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w Enoch|strong="G1802"\w*, \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w seventh|strong="G1442"\w* \w from|strong="G2064"\w* Adam, \w prophesied|strong="G4395"\w* \w about|strong="G1722"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w men|strong="G3778"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w Look|strong="G2400"\w*, \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w is|strong="G3778"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w ten|strong="G1722"\w* \w thousands|strong="G3461"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G1722"\w* holy ones
\v 15 \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w execute|strong="G4160"\w* \w judgment|strong="G2920"\w* \w on|strong="G2596"\w* \w everyone|strong="G3956"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w convict|strong="G1651"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* godless \w among|strong="G2596"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* godless \w deeds|strong="G2041"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* godlessly perpetrated, \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w harsh|strong="G4642"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w spoken|strong="G2980"\w* \w against|strong="G2596"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*—\w the|strong="G2532"\w* godless sinners!”\f + \fr 1:15 \ft Since I believe that Jude was inspired by the Holy Spirit in writing this letter, then I understand that Enoch, the seventh from Adam, actually did write a prophecy and copies still existed in Jude's day. Note that this affirms the historicity/accuracy of the Genesis genealogy. If Enoch wrote, Adam also wrote, and their writings were preserved in Noah's Ark, becoming available for use by Moses and others. If the language spoken before the Flood was a type of Hebrew, as I assume, then Jude could easily read it. No copies of this prophecy in Hebrew are known today, though Jews are reported to have used one as late as the 13\sup th\sup* century \sc ad\sc* A few supposed copies in other languages have been found.\f*
\v 16 \w These|strong="G3778"\w* \w men|strong="G3778"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w grumblers|strong="G1113"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w complainers|strong="G3202"\w*, living \w according|strong="G2596"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* own \w evil|strong="G2532"\w* \w desires|strong="G1939"\w*; \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w talk|strong="G2980"\w* big, \w flattering|strong="G2296"\w* \w people|strong="G1510"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* gain \w advantage|strong="G5622"\w*.
\s1 Exhortation
\p 
\v 17 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, dear ones, \w remember|strong="G3403"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w words|strong="G4487"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* spoken \w before|strong="G4302"\w* \w by|strong="G5259"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* Apostles \w of|strong="G5259"\w* \w our|strong="G2424"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*:
\v 18 \w how|strong="G3754"\w* \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w told|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w in|strong="G1909"\w* \w the|strong="G1909"\w* \w last|strong="G2078"\w* \w time|strong="G5550"\w* \w there|strong="G3754"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w scoffers|strong="G1703"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* live \w according|strong="G2596"\w* \w to|strong="G2596"\w* \w their|strong="G1438"\w* \w own|strong="G1438"\w* godless \w desires|strong="G1939"\w*.
\v 19 \w These|strong="G3778"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* ones \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w cause|strong="G3588"\w* division; \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* ‘soulish’, \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w having|strong="G2192"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w spirit|strong="G4151"\w*.\f + \fr 1:19 \ft There is no definite article with “spirit”, so Jude is probably not referring to the Holy Spirit here. He says that the people being described are characterized by soul, not having a spirit. In which case, the reference is to humanoids, the offspring of demons with women; like it was in the days of Noah (note Genesis 6:4—“\bd and also afterward\bd*”). Don't forget our Lord's words in Matthew 24:37. If/since there are such humanoids among us today, our total ignorance on the subject is having very serious consequences in the culture at large. For more on this subject, please see my article, “As were the days of Noah”, available from my website: www.prunch.org.\f*
\p 
\v 20 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, dear ones, \w building|strong="G2026"\w* \w yourselves|strong="G1438"\w* \w up|strong="G2026"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w your|strong="G1722"\w* most \w holy|strong="G4151"\w* \w faith|strong="G4102"\w*, \w praying|strong="G4336"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Holy|strong="G4151"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w*,
\v 21 \w keep|strong="G5083"\w* \w yourselves|strong="G1438"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*'\w s|strong="G2962"\w* love,\f + \fr 1:21 \ft This is an interesting concept; we are to keep ourselves in God's love. Two of the means toward that end are given in verse 20.\f* \w looking|strong="G4327"\w* \w forward|strong="G1519"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w mercy|strong="G1656"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* eternal \w life|strong="G2222"\w*.\f + \fr 1:21 \ft Our final entrance into eternal life is stated to derive from our Lord's mercy.\f*
\p 
\v 22 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* merciful \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w some|strong="G3739"\w*, \w making|strong="G2532"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w distinction|strong="G1252"\w*;\f + \fr 1:22 \ft Verses 22 and 23 have given all sorts of exercise to commentators (and to copyists who produced Greek manuscripts, before them). Considering the violent description that Jude gives to the godless who have sneaked into the church, he presumably intends that such be identified and excluded without ceremony. So I take it that verses 22 and 23 refer to people in the church who have been influenced by those godless ones, in varying degrees. Some who are still wavering need to be treated with mercy, not harshly (v. 22). Others have pretty well sold out to the values of the godless and are almost to the point of no return—it will take energetic, if not desperate, action to snatch them from the jaws of hell (v. 23). You can't ‘snatch’ without direct contact, and there is the danger of contamination.\f*
\v 23 \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w others|strong="G3588"\w* \w save|strong="G4982"\w* \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w fear|strong="G5401"\w*, snatching \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w fire|strong="G4442"\w*, \w hating|strong="G3404"\w* \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w garment|strong="G5509"\w* \w stained|strong="G4695"\w* \w by|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w*.\f + \fr 1:23 \ft 1 John 2:15 says: “Do not love the world or the things in the world. If anyone loves the world, the love of the Father is not in him.” In a similar vein Jude warns against allowing oneself to be contaminated by anything attached to the people who are being rescued—everything about them will be contaminated by Satan's germs.\f*
\s1 Doxology
\p 
\v 24 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w able|strong="G1410"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w keep|strong="G5442"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*\f + \fr 1:24 \ft Virtually all versions in English read ‘you’, following some 30% of the Greek manuscripts; but the 68% (there are two further variants), including the best line of transmission, read “them”, and in the context “them” makes good sense. Jude is assuring his readers that it is worth the effort to snatch people from the very jaws of hell (v. 23), because God is able to secure them (one's natural tendency would be to doubt that). In commenting the parable of the lost sheep, the Lord Jesus affirmed that “there will be more joy in heaven over one sinner who repents than over ninety-nine just persons who need no repentance.” It seems that God gets special pleasure out of cheating the Lake. Remembering that every human being bears the image of the Creator, we can understand why.\f* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* stumbling \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w present|strong="G2476"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w before|strong="G1722"\w* \w His|strong="G1722"\w* \w glorious|strong="G1391"\w* \w presence|strong="G2714"\w* \w without|strong="G2532"\w* fault \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w with|strong="G1722"\w* exultation\f + \fr 1:24 \ft This is truly marvelous: someone who was snatched from the jaws of hell is transformed to the extent that he can stand before God “without fault”. God Himself will exult (Luke 15:10).\f*—
\v 25 \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w Savior|strong="G4990"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w alone|strong="G3441"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* wise,\f + \fr 1:25 \ft About 8% of the Greek manuscripts omit “wise”, leaving ‘to the only God our Savior’ (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w majesty|strong="G3172"\w*, \w power|strong="G1849"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w authority|strong="G1849"\w*, \w both|strong="G2532"\w* \w now|strong="G3568"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w throughout|strong="G1519"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* ages! Amen. 
